---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { demoBySlug, BUILD_ID } from '../../consts';
const demo = demoBySlug('catch');
---

<Base title={demo.title} description={demo.description}>
  <link slot="head" rel="stylesheet" href={`/css/demo.css?v=${BUILD_ID}`} />
  <section class="demo-wrap container">
    <header class="demo-head">
      <a class="demo-back" href="/demos/">← All demos</a>
      <h1>{demo.title}</h1>
      <p class="demo-lede">{demo.description}</p>
    </header>

    <!-- The whole game is this one canvas. No DOM game elements at all. -->
    <div class="stage stage-catch" id="catch-stage" data-immersive>
      <canvas id="catch-canvas"></canvas>
      <div class="catch-hint">
        Move with the mouse or the &larr;&nbsp;&rarr; keys &middot; catch the fruit named at the top
        &middot; no clicks needed
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="demo-explain">
      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <div class="explain-grid">
        <div class="explain-card explain-win">
          <h4>Truly zero DOM</h4>
          <p>
            Fruit, the catcher, the goal, the HUD, and the win screen are <em>all</em> drawn on one
            <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> by a single VectoJS <code>Entity</code>. There is not one
            <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> in the game — input is just mouse-move and arrow keys.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="explain-card">
          <h4>One Entity, one loop</h4>
          <p>
            The engine's <code>Scene</code> drives the entity's <code>update(dt)</code> for physics and
            <code>render(r)</code> for drawing every frame — falling fruit, catch detection, and the
            HUD are plain arithmetic over the <code>IRenderer</code>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="explain-card">
          <h4>The challenge</h4>
          <p>
            A random goal each round — say <em>“Catch 3 Apples.”</em> You get five catches: a target
            fills the goal, a wrong fruit wastes one. Reach the count to pass; run out of the five to
            fail. Goal and drop positions reshuffle every round.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="demo-explain">
      <h2>VectoJS vs PixiJS</h2>
      <p class="compare-lede">
        Both render this game to a canvas with zero extra DOM. The real difference is what each tool
        is <em>for</em> — a UI framework versus a 2D rendering library.
      </p>
      <div class="compare-scroll">
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead>
            <tr
              ><th scope="col">Aspect</th><th scope="col">VectoJS</th><th scope="col">PixiJS</th
              ></tr
            >
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">What it is</th>
              <td>A UI framework — accessible components, layout, and text on a canvas.</td>
              <td>A 2D rendering library — a fast WebGL/WebGPU scene graph.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Drawing model</th>
              <td>
                Retained entity tree; you draw each entity imperatively in <code>render(r)</code> through
                an <code>IRenderer</code>.
              </td>
              <td>
                Retained scene graph of display objects (<code>Sprite</code>, <code>Graphics</code>,
                <code>Text</code>) that it batches for you.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">This game</th>
              <td>One <code>Entity</code>; the fruit are plain data drawn each frame.</td>
              <td
                >A <code>Graphics</code>/<code>Sprite</code> per fruit, mutated inside a <code
                  >Ticker</code
                >.</td
              >
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Accessibility</th>
              <td>
                Every interactive entity projects a real DOM node automatically — screen readers,
                Playwright, and IME just work.
              </td>
              <td
                >Canvas is opaque to assistive tech; an opt-in plugin overlays DOM for interactive
                objects.</td
              >
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Text &amp; layout</th>
              <td
                >Built-in layout engine — wrapping, rich text, Markdown, and flow around shapes.</td
              >
              <td
                ><code>Text</code>/<code>BitmapText</code>; positioning is manual (layout via a
                separate plugin).</td
              >
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">DOM for this game</th>
              <td>Zero</td>
              <td>Zero</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="compare-note">
        PixiJS is the mature, battle-tested choice for high-throughput 2D — heavy sprite and
        particle scenes, and games. VectoJS's bet is different: treat the whole interface, not just
        the game layer, as a mathematical canvas with accessibility and layout built in. Here the
        same game collapses to a single <code>Entity</code> and is accessible-ready by construction.
        See
        <a href="/blog/layout-and-typography/">Layout and Typography on Canvas</a> for the reasoning.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>
</Base>

<script>
  import '../../demos/catch';
  import '../../demos/immersive';
</script>

<style>
  /* A soft night-orchard backdrop; the canvas itself is transparent and draws the
     game over this. Keeping the background in CSS means the game stays zero-DOM. */
  #catch-stage {
    background: radial-gradient(120% 90% at 50% -10%, #24314f 0%, #131b30 45%, #0a1020 100%);
  }
  #catch-canvas {
    touch-action: none; /* drag to move the catcher without scrolling the page */
  }
  .catch-hint {
    position: absolute;
    left: 50%;
    bottom: 0.7rem;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    color: rgba(226, 232, 240, 0.72);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    text-align: center;
    pointer-events: none;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  /* VectoJS vs PixiJS comparison */
  .compare-lede,
  .compare-note {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.65;
    max-width: 72ch;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .compare-note {
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
  }
  .compare-scroll {
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin: 1.4rem 0 0;
  }
  .compare-table {
    width: 100%;
    min-width: 640px;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .compare-table th,
  .compare-table td {
    text-align: left;
    padding: 0.7rem 0.9rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  .compare-table thead th {
    color: #fff;
    font-weight: 700;
    border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.12);
  }
  .compare-table thead th:nth-child(2) {
    color: #7dd3fc;
  }
  .compare-table tbody th {
    color: #cbd5e1;
    font-weight: 600;
    white-space: nowrap;
    width: 1%;
  }
  .compare-table td {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .compare-table code {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 0.85em;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
    padding: 0.05em 0.35em;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: #cbd5e1;
  }
</style>
